[src:background-sync/api-syncevent] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:background-sync/api-syncevent] The **`SyncEvent`** interface of the Background Synchronization API represents a sync action that is dispatched on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope` of a ServiceWorker.
[src:background-sync/api-syncevent] This interface inherits from the `ExtendableEvent` interface.
[src:background-sync/api-syncevent] Returns the developer-defined identifier for this `SyncEvent`.
[src:background-sync/api-syncevent] Returns `true` if the user agent will not make further synchronization attempts after the current attempt.
[src:background-sync/api-syncmanager] The **`SyncManager`** interface of the Background Synchronization API provides an interface for registering and listing sync registrations.
[src:background-sync/api-syncmanager] Create a new sync registration and return a `Promise`.
[src:background-sync/api-syncmanager] Return a list of developer-defined identifiers for `SyncManager` registrations.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] The **Background Synchronization API** enables a web app to defer tasks so that they can be run in a service worker once the user has a stable network connection.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] The Background Synchronization API allows web applications to defer server synchronization work to their service worker to handle at a later time, if the device is offline.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] Uses may include sending requests in the background if they couldn't be sent while the application was being used.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] For example, an email client application could let its users compose and send messages at any time, even when the device has no network connection.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] The application frontend just registers a sync request and the service worker gets alerted when the network is present again and handles the sync.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] The `SyncManager` interface is available through `ServiceWorkerRegistration.sync`.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] A unique tag identifier is set to 'name' the sync event, which can then be listened for within the `ServiceWorker` script.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] Once the event is received you can then run any functionality available, such as sending requests to the server.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] As this API relies on service workers, functionality provided by this API is only available in a secure context.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] Registers tasks to be run in a service worker at a later time with network connectivity.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] These tasks are referred to as *background sync requests*.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] Represents a synchronization event, sent to the global scope of a `ServiceWorker`.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] It provides a way to run tasks in the service worker once the device has network connectivity.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] The following additions to the Service Worker API provide an entry point for setting up background synchronization.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] Returns a reference to the `SyncManager` interface for registering tasks to run once the device has network connectivity.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] An event handler fired whenever a `sync` event occurs.
[src:background-sync/background-synchronization-api] This happens as soon as the network becomes available.
