[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Data synchronization is needed to update and keep multiple copies of a set of data coherent with one another or to maintain data integrity, Figure 3.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] For example, database replication is used to keep multiple copies of data synchronized with database servers that store data in different locations.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Data formats tend to grow more complex with time as the organization grows and evolves.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] This results not only in building simple interfaces between the two applications (source and target), but also in a need to transform the data while passing them to the target application.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] ETL (extraction transformation loading) tools can be helpful at this stage for managing data format complexities.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] In real-time systems, customers want to see the current status of their order in e-shop, the current status of a parcel delivery—a real time parcel tracking—, the current balance on their account, etc.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] This shows the need of a real-time system, which is being updated as well to enable smooth manufacturing process in real-time, e.g., ordering material when enterprise is running out stock, synchronizing customer orders with manufacturing process, etc.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] From real life, there exist so many examples where real-time processing gives successful and competitive advantage.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] There are no fixed rules and policies to enforce data security.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] It may vary depending on the system which you are using.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Even though the security is maintained correctly in the source system which captures the data, the security and information access privileges must be enforced on the target systems as well to prevent any potential misuse of the information.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] This is a serious issue and particularly when it comes for handling secret, confidential and personal information.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] So because of the sensitivity and confidentiality, data transfer and all in-between information must be encrypted.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Data quality is another serious constraint.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] For better management and to maintain good quality of data, the common practice is to store the data at one location and share with different people and different systems and/or applications from different locations.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] It helps in preventing inconsistencies in the data.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] In case of large amounts of data, the synchronization process needs to be carefully planned and executed to avoid any negative impact on performance.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] There are tools available for file synchronization, version control (CVS, Subversion, etc.), distributed filesystems (Coda, etc.), and mirroring (rsync, etc.), in that all these attempt to keep sets of files synchronized.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] However, only version control and file synchronization tools can deal with modifications to more than one copy of the files.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Several theoretical models of data synchronization exist in the research literature, and the problem is also related to the problem of Slepian–Wolf coding in information theory.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] The models are classified based on how they consider the data to be synchronized.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] The problem of synchronizing unordered data (also known as the **set reconciliation problem**) is modeled as an attempt to compute the symmetric difference $S_{A}\oplus S_{B}=(S_{A}-S_{B})\cup (S_{B}-S_{A})$ between two remote sets $S_{A}$ and $S_{B}$ of b-bit numbers.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] In this case all data is transferred to one host for a local comparison.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] In this case all changes to the data are marked with timestamps.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Synchronization proceeds by transferring all data with a timestamp later than the previous synchronization.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] In this case data are treated as mathematical objects and synchronization corresponds to a mathematical process.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] In this case, two remote strings $\sigma _{A}$ and $\sigma _{B}$ need to be reconciled.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Typically, it is assumed that these strings differ by up to a fixed number of **edits** (i.e. character insertions, deletions, or modifications).
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Then data synchronization is the process of reducing edit distance between $\sigma _{A}$ and $\sigma _{B}$ , up to the ideal distance of zero.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] This is applied in all filesystem based synchronizations (where the data is ordered).
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Many practical applications of this are discussed or referenced above.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] It is sometimes possible to transform the problem to one of unordered data through a process known as shingling (splitting the strings into *shingles*).
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] In fault-tolerant systems, distributed databases must be able to cope with the loss or corruption of (part of) their data.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] The first step is usually replication, which involves making multiple copies of the data and keeping them all up to date as changes are made.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] However, it is then necessary to decide which copy to rely on when loss or corruption of an instance occurs.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] The simplest approach is to have a single master instance that is the sole source of truth.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Changes to it are replicated to other instances, and one of those instances becomes the new master when the old master fails.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Paxos and Raft are more complex protocols that exist to solve problems with transient effects during failover, such as two instances thinking they are the master at the same time.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] Secret sharing is useful if failures of whole nodes are very common.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] This moves synchronization from an explicit recovery process to being part of each read, where a read of some data requires retrieving encoded data from several different nodes.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] If corrupt or out-of-date data may be present on some nodes, this approach may also benefit from the use of an error correction code.
[src:background-sync/data-synchronization] DHTs and Blockchains try to solve the problem of synchronization between many nodes (hundreds to billions).
[src:background-sync/offline] In computer technology and telecommunications, **online** indicates a state of connectivity, and **offline** indicates a disconnected state.
[src:background-sync/offline] In modern terminology, this usually refers to an Internet connection, but (especially when expressed as "on line" or "on the line") could refer to any piece of equipment or functional unit that is connected to a larger system.
[src:background-sync/offline] Being online means that the equipment or subsystem is connected, or that it is ready for use.
[src:background-sync/offline] "Online" has come to describe activities and concepts that take place on the Internet, such as online identity, online predator and online shop.
[src:background-sync/offline] A similar meaning is also given by the prefixes cyber and e, as in words *cyberspace*, *cybercrime*, *email*, and *e-commerce*.
[src:background-sync/offline] In contrast, "offline" can refer to either computing activities performed while disconnected from the Internet, or alternatives to Internet activities (such as shopping in brick-and-mortar stores).
[src:background-sync/offline] The term "offline" is sometimes used interchangeably with the acronym "IRL", meaning "in real life", as well as about office meetings in person wherein a formal, high-concentration meeting may have matters taken "offline" to a more relaxed moment away from the "online" high-stress meeting.
[src:background-sync/offline] During the 19th century, the term *on line* was commonly used in both the railroad and telegraph industries.
[src:background-sync/offline] For railroads, a signal box would send messages down the line (track), via a telegraph line (cable), indicating the track's status: *Train on line* or *Line clear*.
[src:background-sync/offline] Telegraph linemen would refer to sending current through a line as *direct on line* or *battery on line*; or they may refer to a problem with the circuit as being *on line*, as opposed to the power source or end-point equipment.
[src:background-sync/offline] Since at least 1950, in computing, the terms *on-line* and *off-line* have been used to refer to whether machines, including computers and peripheral devices, are connected or not.
[src:background-sync/offline] The use of automatic computing equipment for large-scale reduction of data will be strikingly successful only if means are provided for the automatic transcription of these data to a form suitable for automatic entry into the machine.
[src:background-sync/offline] In on-line operation the input is communicated directly and without delay to the data-reduction device.
[src:background-sync/offline] operation, involving automatic transcription of data in a form suitable for later introduction to the machine, may be tolerated.
[src:background-sync/offline] For example, some teletype machines operate on line.
[src:background-sync/offline] Their operators are in instantaneous communication.
[src:background-sync/offline] The message is preserved by means of holes punched in the tape and is transmitted later by feeding the tape to another machine.
[src:background-sync/offline] One example of a common use of these concepts with email is a mail user agent (MUA) that can be instructed to be in either online or offline states.
[src:background-sync/offline] When online it will attempt to connect to mail servers (to check for new mail at regular intervals, for example), and when offline it will not attempt to make any such connection.
[src:background-sync/offline] Similarly, a computer may be configured to employ a dial-up connection on demand (as when an application such as Outlook attempts to make a connection to a server), but the user may not wish for Outlook to trigger that call whenever it is configured to check for mail.
[src:background-sync/offline] Another example of the use of these concepts is digital audio technology.
[src:background-sync/offline] A tape recorder, digital audio editor, or other device that is online is one whose clock is under the control of the clock of a synchronization master device.
[src:background-sync/offline] When the sync master commences playback, the online device automatically synchronizes itself to the master and commences playing from the same point in the recording.
[src:background-sync/offline] A device that is offline uses no external clock reference and relies upon its own internal clock.
[src:background-sync/offline] A third example of a common use of these concepts is a web browser that can be instructed to be in either online or offline states.
[src:background-sync/offline] The browser attempts to fetch pages from servers while only in the online state.
[src:background-sync/offline] In the offline state, or "offline mode", users can perform **offline browsing**, where pages can be browsed using local copies of those pages that have previously been downloaded while in the online state.
[src:background-sync/offline] This can be useful when the computer is offline and connection to the Internet is impossible or undesirable.
[src:background-sync/offline] One such web browser is Internet Explorer.
[src:background-sync/offline] When pages are added to the Favourites list, they can be marked to be "available for offline browsing".
[src:background-sync/offline] Internet Explorer will download local copies of both the marked page and, optionally, all of the pages that it links to.
[src:background-sync/offline] In Internet Explorer version 6, the level of direct and indirect links, the maximum amount of local disc space allowed to be consumed, and the schedule on which local copies are checked to see whether they are up-to-date, are configurable for each individual Favourites entry.
[src:background-sync/offline] More recently, the Internet Archive announced an offline server project intended to provide access to material on inexpensive servers that can be updated using USB sticks and SD cards.
[src:background-sync/offline] Likewise, offline storage is computer data storage that has no connection to the other systems until a connection is deliberately made.
[src:background-sync/offline] Additionally, an otherwise online system that is powered down may be considered offline.
[src:background-sync/offline] With the growing communication tools and media, the words offline and online are used very frequently.
[src:background-sync/offline] If a person is active over a messaging tool and is able to accept the messages it is termed as online message and if the person is not available and the message is left to view when the person is back, it is termed as offline message.
[src:background-sync/offline] In the same context, the person's availability is termed as online and non-availability is termed as offline.
[src:background-sync/offline] In the context of file systems, *online* and *offline* are synonymous with *mounted* and *not mounted*.
[src:background-sync/offline] For example, in file systems' resizing capabilities, *online grow* and *online shrink* respectively mean the ability to increase or decrease the space allocated to that file system without needing to unmount it.
[src:background-sync/offline] Online and offline distinctions have been generalised from computing and telecommunication into the field of human interpersonal relationships.
[src:background-sync/offline] The distinction between what is considered online and what is considered offline has become a subject of study in the field of sociology.
[src:background-sync/offline] The distinction between online and offline is conventionally seen as the distinction between computer-mediated communication and face-to-face communication (e.g., face time), respectively.
[src:background-sync/offline] Online is virtuality or cyberspace, and offline is reality (i.e., real life or "meatspace").
[src:background-sync/offline] Slater states that this distinction is "obviously far too simple".
[src:background-sync/offline] To support his argument that the distinctions in relationships are more complex than a simple dichotomy of online versus offline, he observes that some people draw no distinction between an online relationship, such as indulging in cybersex, and an offline relationship, such as being pen pals.
[src:background-sync/offline] He also conjectures that an online/offline distinction may be seen by people as "rather quaint and not quite comprehensible" within 10 years.
[src:background-sync/offline] This distinction between *online* and *offline* is sometimes inverted, with online concepts being used to define and to explain offline activities, rather than (as per the conventions of the desktop metaphor with its desktops, trash cans, folders, and so forth) the other way around.
[src:background-sync/offline] Several cartoons appearing in *The New Yorker* have satirized this.
[src:background-sync/offline] One includes Saint Peter asking for a username and a password before admitting a man into Heaven.
[src:background-sync/serviceworkerregistration-sync] The **`sync`** read-only property of the `ServiceWorkerRegistration` interface returns a reference to the `SyncManager` interface, which manages background synchronization processes.
